'''Anekurahime Shrine''' (あねくらひめじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Toyama City|Q204266|qid=Q204266|1=Toyama (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Toyama Prefecture|Q132929|qid=Q132929|1=Toyama Prefecture}}. It is also written as '''Anekura-hime Shrine'''. The shrine is built atop an ancient burial mound (kofun).

There are two shrines of the same name within Toyama City ({{ill|lt=Kureha Town (Toyama City)|Q86731852|qid=Q86731852|lt=Kureha-hime origin shrine|1=Kureha-hime origin shrine}} and Funakura). Both are considered candidate shrines (ronsha) of the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} “Anekurahime Shrine of {{ill|lt=Etchū Province|Q906899|qid=Q906899|1=Etchū Province}}, {{ill|lt=Nei District|Q6987940|qid=Q6987940|1=Nei District, Toyama}}.” Both formerly held the rank of {{ill|lt=Village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The {{ill|lt=enshrined deity|Q11591100|qid=Q11591100|1=Saijin}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Anekurahime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}. According to a synthesis of the shrine traditions of both shrines, Anekurahime-no-Kami subdued bandits in the region, established her residence on Mount Funakura, ruled the area, and spread agriculture, sericulture, and weaving among the local people. In the “Sentatsuroku,” Anekurahime-no-Kami was married to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Isurugi-hiko-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}} of Noto (the enshrined deity of {{ill|lt=Isurugi-hiko Shrine|Q11381009|qid=Q11381009|1=Isurugi Hikojinja}}). However, Isurugi-hiko-no-Kami entered into a relationship with {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Noto-hime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}} of Mount Senbokuyama (the enshrined deity of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Noto-hime Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}). Enraged, Anekurahime-no-Kami hurled stones from Mount Funakura to attack Noto-hime-no-Kami. Anekurahime-no-Kami’s younger sister, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Fukurahime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, also joined the attack, plunging the land of Koshi into great turmoil. {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}} of Izumo was dispatched to Koshi by order of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Takami-musubi-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, and together with five assembled deities, he suppressed the rebellion. As punishment for causing the disturbance, Anekurahime-no-Kami was stripped of her territory and exiled to Kureha Kotake, where she was ordered to teach weaving to the local women. Fukurahime-no-Kami received the same punishment. Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and the others then attacked the remaining two deities and ultimately executed Isurugi-hiko-no-Kami and Noto-hime-no-Kami on the seashore.

The place name “Nei District” (婦負郡) is derived from Anekurahime-no-Kami, and the place name “Kureha” is also associated with weaving.

At the Kureha Anekurahime Shrine, {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|Q455602|qid=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}}, Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, and {{ill|qid=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata-no-Kami|UNKNOWN|qid=Q9150391|lt=Takeminakata-no-Mikoto|1=Takeminakata}} are additionally enshrined as principal deities<ref name="p111" />.

=== Overview ===
;Kureha-hime origin shrine
*Location – 1813 Kureha Town, Toyama City, Toyama Prefecture<ref name="p111">“Toyama Prefecture Shrine Gazetteer” (November 10, 1983), edited and published by the Toyama Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines, p. 111.</ref>.
*Shrine grounds – 3,950 tsubo (formerly located on a keyhole-shaped tumulus)<ref name="p111" />

:It is said to be the oldest shrine in Etchū Province<ref name="p111" />. Nearby, it served as a base for {{ill|lt=Uesugi Kenshin|Q311080|qid=Q311080|1=Uesugi Kenshin}}’s march to the capital ({{ill|lt=jōraku|Q10867576|qid=Q10867576|1=Joraku}}). In {{ill|lt=1537|Q6461|qid=Q6461|1=1537}} ({{ill|lt=Tenbun|Q1145754|qid=Q1145754|1=Genbun}} 7), 200 koku of shrine lands were donated, and on {{ill|lt=February 26|Q2359|qid=Q2359|1=February 26}}, {{ill|lt=1546|Q6533|qid=Q6533|1=1546}} ({{ill|lt=Eiroku|Q1143341|qid=Q1143341|1=Eiroku}} 7), a written prayer was dedicated to the shrine. On {{ill|lt=July 17|Q2729|qid=Q2729|1=July 17}}, {{ill|lt=1721|Q6913|qid=Q6913|1=1721}} ({{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 5), the Tanaka Shrine was transferred and jointly enshrined. In {{ill|lt=1870|Q7741|qid=Q7741|1=1870}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 3), the main hall was rebuilt, and on {{ill|lt=May 11|Q2558|qid=Q2558|1=May 11}}, {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|qid=Q7766|1=1876}} (Meiji 9), the Shinmei Shrine was transferred and jointly enshrined. In {{ill|lt=1897|Q7847|qid=Q7847|1=1897}} (Meiji 30), the shrine buildings were rebuilt. In {{ill|lt=1955|Q18577|qid=Q18577|1=1955}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 30), a new protective roof over the sanctuary was constructed, and in {{ill|lt=1978|Q2483|qid=Q2483|1=1978}} (Shōwa 53), the worship hall underwent major repairs. (“Toyama Prefecture Shrine Gazetteer,” p. 112.)

;Funakura
*Location – 2360 Funakura, Toyama City, Toyama Prefecture<ref name="p157">“Toyama Prefecture Shrine Gazetteer” (November 10, 1983), edited and published by the Toyama Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines, p. 157.</ref>.
*Shrine grounds – 13,157 tsubo<ref name="p157" />

:Founded during the {{ill|lt=Taihō era|Q1346269|qid=Q1346269|1=Taihō (era)}} (when the monk Kifuku established the Shingon Buddhist temple Jōryū-ji). After Jōryū-ji burned down during the {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} era, the shrine is said to have been established on its former site. On {{ill|lt=April 20|Q2524|qid=Q2524|1=April 20}}, {{ill|lt=1906|Q2049|qid=Q2049|1=1906}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 39), it was listed as a formerly designated shrine<ref name="p157" />.

